# Examples and Test Data Policy

This project must maintain a small but stable set of reference input cases for regression safety.

## Required reference cases

Keep and maintain at least these reference cases:

1. minimal steady-state case
2. minimal transient case
3. radiation-enabled case
4. arithmetic-node case

These cases should live under `examples/` and/or `tests/data/`.

## Purpose of reference cases

Reference cases are used to:
- verify parser stability
- verify solver execution still works
- verify output files are still generated
- detect accidental numerical regressions
- provide small known-good inputs for future UI and FreeCAD integration testing

## Keep cases small and deterministic

- Prefer small node counts.
- Prefer deterministic inputs with simple expected behavior.
- Avoid unnecessarily large real-world models for regression tests.
- Keep reference cases fast to run.

## Do not silently modify reference cases

- Do not edit reference input files casually.
- If a reference case must change, explain:
  - what changed
  - why it changed
  - what old behavior is no longer expected
  - whether regression baselines must be updated

## Prefer one concept per case

Each reference case should primarily test one main concept:
- steady solve
- transient stepping
- radiation handling
- arithmetic node handling
- boundary node behavior
- output generation

Avoid making every test case cover too many concepts at once.

## Keep expected outputs lightweight

- Prefer checking a few representative temperatures or output conditions.
- Prefer tolerances over exact string matching for numerical values.
- Avoid brittle checks on full file formatting unless formatting is the feature under test.

## When fixing a bug

When a parser or solver bug is fixed:
- add a new reference case or
- extend an existing test
so the same bug is less likely to return.

## Compatibility expectation

Unless explicitly instructed otherwise:
- existing reference cases should continue to run
- their main expected behavior should remain valid
- file naming and output generation should remain broadly compatible